I have three printers: PowerSpec 3D Printer Pro, a Delta printer I built, and a Printrbot Simple Metal. The Delta is the most versatile with a 300mm diameter print bed and 375mm print height. It's driven by an Azteeg X5 mini v3 controller running Smoothieware, 0.9 degree steppers, E3D v6 hot end with direct drive extruder and a heated PEI bed. The frame is 6020 v-slot extruded aluminum from OpenBuilds. I'm in the process of adding linear rails for the carriages, which use magnetic ball rods and ends. The rods are from Haydn Huntley and have Delrin ends. I use Octoprint to drive the printer over WiFi. My slicing software is Simplify3D. For the Printrbot Simple Metal I added a heated bed, which works well for PLA and PET-G. The latter printer is a great workhorse despite being a little noisy; it produces precise parts. My PowerSpec has been sitting idle for several months since it needs some adjustments that I haven't gotten around to. It's a great printer that really got me started with 3D printing.

bio:
Anchorage’s Makers are an enthusiastic group of hobbyists and professionals that identify with the “maker culture” — a movement which encourages experimentation and invention in The Arts and Sciences. The strength of a group is in its members, so if you like to build things (or take them apart), hack hardware, write software, design electronics, work with wood, metal, fiberglass, or plastic, grow your own food, or just look up at the stars and wonder how it all works… well, you’re in the right place.

The Anchorage Makerspace (AMS) is a place for Startups, Evil Genius’s, Infovores, Creative Artists and all who Aspire to Learn More:

Startup Design and Prototyping Space: At the AMS you will find a competent fabrication shop for your Business Startup. As a Non-Profit Corporation, we are Anchorage’s most flexible design and fabrication shop. Becoming a member gives you 24/7 access to all the tools and resources we have available – an unbeatable deal.
Unleash your Evil Genius! If you ever wanted to build a ray-gun or lightsaber, but were missing the tools, workspace (and motivation), you will find your tribe at the AMS! Projects underway are a retro MAME Arcade machine, plasma speakers and a whole slew of home, car and lifestyle automation projects.
Are you an Insatiable Infovore? Ever wanted to learn how to weld? What about pottery? Have you wanted to build a network served media center for your home, from where you can access all your movies and music? We offer classes in introductory to advanced robotics, how to program an Arduino microcontroller, or just learn how connect up hundreds of LEDs for your home projects at our classes. Do you need help with your Math or Science courses? Yep, we have that too! These and a whole lot more peer-taught basic to advanced classes are on offer.

I mostly model props from science fiction movies, TV shows, and computer games that I enjoy. If I like the way they turn out, I post them here for others who share the same fandoms. This is just a personal hobby; I don't take commissions or sell prints.

If you're the sort of person who hates post-print finishing, you probably won't enjoy my models much. I tend to design them in sections, both for best FDM printing results and for ease of smoothing and painting; they'll almost always need some assembly afterwards. Sometimes a LOT of assembly. I also design them for relatively high vertical resolution (0.12mm layers or less); printing in lower resolution may cause assembly difficulties (especially parts that screw together).

I enjoy seeing makes of my models! Selling prints on eBay/Etsy/whatever is fine, but I release the models as CC-Attribution, so please credit me and post a Thingiverse link in your listing.

If you have trouble printing one of my models, please let me know, and I'll see if I can help with whatever the issue is.

Bought my Anet A8 as a newbie to 3D printing myself (watched a ton of videos since I was interested in it before) because I searched on ebay for the cheapest printer out there, found the A8 and searched it up in google and youtube, it had good and bad reviews the good ones saying that it's a good printer when you're a tinkerer and the bad ones that you have to tinker with it, I'm pretty much into electronics, computers and mechanics so it wasn't that big deal and I bought it for 150 € from a seller from germany.
It arrived after 2 days (there was a bank holiday between buy and shipping so I think it would have arrived next day without a holiday).
Unpacked it and started building it together with instructions from a youtube tutorial, the longest thing at the building was to unwrap the acrylic frame from the paper wrapping which was very anoying (some parts where plastik foil wrap, this wrapping was a dream to take of and i wished that all parts where plastik wrapped).
After the build I started the printer, heated it up and leveled the bed, took the calibration cube and printed it, I was stunned, I had printed the cube with .2mm layer height with the default settings of repetier and it was such a clean looking print, with my calipers I checked the dimensions and they where bang on 20x20x20 mm !!!

Since then I printed and done many improvements to my A8, the best ones are the R3D V6 Bowden upgrade which leaded into fast X speeds and the glass bed which is awesome, no more ripped up tape and bed leveling is a charm, I was interested to add a bed level sensor but with the level screws just screwing into the wing nuts it takes 5 minutes to level the bed properly without moving the glass around.

For now I'm looking forward to build my own printer (I got interested into 3D printing and wanted to build a printer myself in the first place, but I would have needed 3d printed parts for it, and nobopdy from my friends has a printer lolz), so right now I'm doing designing and research for the build of the printer.
